feedback:
looked for similarities/differences and tried to remember them
i noticed that one of the 3 circles that i think should have been a #1 actually showed up as a #2 in the second task at the beginning.
Out of 100 samples, there can only be so many combinations.  I focused on either singular or multiple attributes and broke the families out that way.
I tried to memorize the patterns
I used information about the features such as amount and position to categorize into families.

I attempted to look at the cards fairly quickly in order to notice patterns rather than dwell on each individual card for too long. For the second experiment, I noticed that the three circles only were in family one, and the middle and right circles tended to be in family 2. For the first, I noticed that the first family tended to only have pieces of their body, especially only a head, while the second one tended to be more complete.

I tried to find patterns for each of the families that made sense, although I'm not sure I accomplished this. I thought family 2 on the first one tended to involve legs more often than not and on the second group, I thought family 1 involved more dots on the left and family 2 involved more dots on the right.
I didn't notice any patterns. I just picked numbers at random.

I tried to figure out any patterns for what normally correlated. For example, with the circles, it seemed like when the center dot was alone, it was family two. If all three circles appeared, it was usually family 1.
Full images with all three characteristics shown were easier to categorize because they tended to appear most obviously in one family or another.
The second set was too confusing
Tried to notice which one went with which family; the ones that were most similar most of the time.
I really did not notice any pattern between family 1 and family 2 in either of the two experiments.
I tried to take most notice of which family the figures with the most features belonged. This was my strategy for categorizing the two.

I actually cannot think of any conscious strategies - I just tried to focus on patterns that I saw. Across 100 trials, it became very difficult to remember patterns, so I believe I just decided on a pattern and fell victim to the confirmation bias in attempting to fit each family into those predetermined categories.

the first one i just put arms/legs together in group 2, anything else in group 1.

second one i just threw any right ball in group 2, everything else in group 1.  

these were total guesses it looked random to me.

With the figures of the people I used groupings of head, arm and leg combos (with or without head, head with arms, head with legs, head with arms and legs). For the circles I used the number of circles and their position on the rectangle.

For the people, most families were in 1 if they didn't have arms. Most families were in 2 if they had a head.

For the circles, most families were a 1 if they appeared on the left side and families were a 2 if they appeared on the right. 

For both families, I would occasionally hit the opposite button since both characteristics could appear in either family.
I just tried to remember the positions that they were in. I tried my best to remember how the shapes/objects were. I don't know if I did well or not but I believe I did ok.
